@kjrevia @shasnthegame First impression wise, the entire presentation looks pretty decent. Can't wait to put the final version through its paces.

You know, once that's possible for us again. Which looks to be pretty soon!
Also for the record re: LT, I didn't seek that Headline card out. I literally flipped the bottom of the deck over and there it was.

Additionally, the last third of the book mostly just explains the various Kickstarter additions to the game you can use or not, such as the aforementioned chaoa board.

All in all it's not nearly as intimidating as you think when you hear '40-page rulebook'.

But those deemed particularly sensitive or even triggering are clearly marked and can be removed if desired without adversely affecting the experience. They also make up a relatively small percentage of the cards overall. It's a commendable approach: respectful but not dismissive https://t.co/IgHoc9K5fz

But don't take our word of their intentions from us directly. Instead, we'll let them say it themselves from their own rules:

Stay tuned for more @shasnthegame content before the month is out! https://t.co/oil3PM4Wac

The one tiny thing we did find, and it's pretty inconsequential is that page index numbers don't line up correctly after the mid-20s (basically the KS section). Looks like some sections got expanded a couple pages and the index wasn't updated. 

It's nothing to worry about.

A campaign's contents for the most part boil down into three flavorful decks of cards. The first two are Headlines (essentially event cards if you enter certain spots on the map) and Conspiracies (action cards you can aquire and unleash on players later). https://t.co/t6AiShftgW

The larger of the two is naturally the rulebook. I was mildly concerned at the size of it - at first. But it's misleading. The rules layout does a decent job of explaining the major aspects, has examples, doesn't overload page layout, and even has flavor sprinkled throughout. https://t.co/Cw3cy1Vc1c
Now back to those books

@DanThurot Nicely done. Having a variety of review perspectives beyond the common commercialist angle is something the hobby definitely benefits from. 

Not sure we've never addressed cost, but wanting to avoid the standard approach was very much part of our gamer archetype inspiration.

The third & largest deck of cards are Ideology cards which present you with a question and an A/B answer to choose. Ideology cards essentially just give you resources depending on your answer, but the game rewards you over time for staying consistent to a governing philosophy. https://t.co/mSmEk8YNg3

Now a quick word about the issues in this game. All the cards address issues of that particular campaign, including some which can be controversial or difficult. As explained in the rules, the designers felt it necessary to include them since they were real issues of the day. BUT

At the same time, browsing through the various cards it's also impressive how much effort this mostly India-based design team went into capturing not only the elements of their own election and political landscape but that of the US & Brexit. The homework was done, warts and all.

After putting it all (and it did go back together without incident), it's evident they put put a lot of effort into research as well as production quality to make #Shasn a worthwhile area-control based campaign simulator. And we can't wait to get it to our table!

Ideology cards are pretty straightforward, cleanly drawn, and easy to understand - even if the underlying messaging isn't quite as simple. The game also provides an excellent small box to house them, complete with magnetic lid. Necessary? No. Cool? Absolutely. https://t.co/BAdRJc6NbD

One of the two books is a scenario book, allowing you to play out specific scenarios which alter the setup and objectives of a normal playthrough in various ways. And like several aspects of Shasn they are optional, allowing you to tailor your experience further. https://t.co/o7xynYUUin
